t10 Collecting and Exhibiting Marian Objects in Nineteenth-century Britain -- t11 ‘The most interesting apartment in Scotland’: The History and Presentation of Mary, Queen of Scots’ Chambers at the Palace of Holyroodhouse -- t12 Materialising Mary in a Museum: Marian Objects and Authenticity -- tPart Four Mary in Media -- t13 Minstrels of Maelstroms: Mary’s Musical Afterlives -- t14 The Transformations of Mary, Queen of Scots in Early Cinema, 1895–1923 -- t15 Long Live the Queen: The Afterlife of Mary, Queen of Scots in Contemporary Visual Culture -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPresents a new way of examining the historical significance and endurance of Mary, Queen of ScotsDiscusses case studies of how Mary has been remembered from her own time until the present day in the UK, Europe and North AmericaBased on the first-ever census of Mary’s material presence in Scottish and royal heritage collections, comprising of over 2,000 physical objects and imagesExamines visual images of Mary, relics associated with her, commemorative items, Marian tourism and exhibitions and Mary’s place in pop culture, film and televisionUtilises Marian objects as a lens to examine attitudes to gender, religion, ethnicity and politics in the time in which they were producedBrings together scholars and heritage professionals from a wide range of disciplines including history, art history, Scottish literature and media and heritage and museum StudiesMary Queen of Scots (1542-1587) was active as monarch of Scotland for just six years between 1561 and 1567, but her impact as a ruler in Scotland is much less important than her subsequent role in popular culture and imagination. Her story has enjoyed perpetual retelling and reached a global audience over the past four and a half centuries. This collection surveys the exceptionally varied range of objects, literature, art and media that have been produced to commemorate Mary between her own time and the present day. Why is her story so enduring, pervasive, and of such interest to so many different audiences? How have the narratives associated with these objects evolved in response to shifting cultural attitudes? The collection offers a much-needed novel perspective on the Queen of Scots, using an approach at the intersection of early modern, gender and cultural history, museum and heritage studies, and memory studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aQueenszScotlandvBiography. 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aBrown, Rhona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarruthers, Gerard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Nia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Michelle H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuguid, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFountain, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoode, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroundwater, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolder, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacdonald, Catriona M. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcBurney, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRae, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Steven J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re